  "prompt": "What was the most memorable 'viral' story that you had forwarded to your inbox back when there wasn't Facebook and social media yet?",
  "response": "Ah, the pre-social media days of forwarding emails! One of the most memorable \"viral\" stories that circulated via email chains was the **\"Nigerian Prince Scam\"** or **\"419 Scam.\"** This was a classic email hoax where someone claimed to be a wealthy Nigerian prince or government official who needed help transferring a large sum of money out of the country. In exchange for your assistance, you were promised a hefty share of the fortune.\n\nThe emails were often poorly written, filled with dramatic pleas, and asked for personal information or small upfront payments to \"cover fees.\" While it sounds laughable now, it was one of the earliest examples of online scams and became infamous for how widely it spread through forwarded emails.\n\nAnother one that comes to mind is the **\"Crazy Eel in the Toilet\" email**, which claimed that a giant eel had been discovered living in someone's toilet, accompanied by a grainy, photoshopped image. It was one of those absurd, over-the-top stories that people couldn't resist forwarding because it was so bizarre.\n\nThese kinds of emails were the viral content of the late '90s and early 2000s \u2014 a mix of scams, urban legends, and outright hoaxes that spread purely through word-of-mouth (or inbox-to-inbox). It\u2019s nostalgic to think about how much the internet has evolved since then!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
